# Literary Understanding

improves when students understand:

```text id="m9r2qe"
characters
and motivations
```

Reading literature is NOT:

```text id="r3e8qe"
retelling actions
only
```

Students learn:

```text id="x1r5qe"
observe actions
→ identify feelings
→ infer traits
→ explain evidence
```

This develops:

* empathy
* inference
* comprehension
* emotional understanding
* evidence-based interpretation

This becomes:

# Character Thinking

Common misconceptions:

children may believe:

```text id="p6r1qe"
feelings
=
traits
```

or:

```text id="u4e7qe"
single action
defines character
```

Some may:

```text id="c2r8qe"
guess traits
without evidence
```

Example:

students may say:

```text id="k7e3qe"
sad
=
kind
```

without understanding:

```text id="n5r4qe"
feelings
change
traits
tend to stay
```

This skill teaches:

```text id="t8e9qe"
character-evidence reasoning
```

For Grade 3:

focus includes:

* feelings
* traits
* motivations
* actions
* text evidence

Common traits:

* kind
* brave
* honest
* helpful
* patient

Common feelings:

* happy
* sad
* angry
* worried
* excited

